ed the struggle of their families and communities for integration into American society.While focusing on their lives as girls, not the adults they would later become, Klapper draws on the papers of such figures as Henrietta Szold, founder of Hadassah; Edna Ferber, Pulitzer Prize-winning author of Showboat; and Marie Syrkin, literary critic and Zionist. Klapper also analyzes the diaries, memoirs, and letters of hundreds of other girls whose later lives and experiences have been lost to history.Told in an engaging style and filled with colorful "es, the book brings to life a neglected group of fascinating historical figures during a pivotal moment in the development of gender roles, adolescence, and the modern American Jewish community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aJewish girlsxEducationzUnited States. 0aJewish girlszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aJewish girlszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aJewish girlszUnited StatesxSocial life and customsy19th century. 0aJewish girlszUnited StatesxSocial life and customsy20th century. 0aJewish religious education of girlszUnited States. 0aJewish teenagerszUnited StatesxSocial life and customsy19th century. 0aJewish teenagerszUnited StatesxSocial life and customsy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aJewish.  aadolescence.  abook.  abrings.  acommunity.  adevelopment.  aduring.  afascinating.  afigures.  agender.  agroup.  ahistorical.  alife.  amodern.  amoment.  aneglected.  apivotal.  aroles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081474780340uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814748657.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978081474865742